            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>Pulley speed formula</h2>
              <p>
                For a simple belt drive with one driver and one driven pulley,
                the belt speed is the same on both pulleys (ignoring slip). This
                gives the fundamental pulley speed relationship:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="mb-1 text-sm">Belt speed equality:</p>
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">v = π · D₁ · N₁ = π · D₂ · N₂</p>
                <p class="mt-2 mb-1 text-sm">Rearranging:</p>
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  N₂ = N₁ · (D₁ / D₂)<br />
                  D₂ = D₁ · (N₁ / N₂)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Speed ratio</h3>
              <p>
                The <strong>speed ratio</strong> of a belt drive is the ratio of
                driver speed to driven speed:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  Speed ratio R = N₁ / N₂ = D₂ / D₁
                </p>
              </div>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>R &gt; 1</strong> → speed reduction (driven pulley
                  slower, torque increased).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>R &lt; 1</strong> → speed increase (driven pulley
                  faster, torque reduced).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Example: motor and compressor pulley</h2>
              <p>
                Suppose you have a 1750 RPM motor with a 3 in driver pulley, and
                you want about 1000 RPM on the compressor.
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>Given: N₁ = 1750 RPM, D₁ = 3 in, N₂ ≈ 1000 RPM.</li>
                <li>
                  Required driven pulley diameter:
                  <span class="font-mono text-sm">D₂ = D₁ · (N₁ / N₂)</span>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Compute:
                  <span class="font-mono text-sm"
                    >D₂ = 3 × (1750 / 1000) ≈ 5.25 in</span
                  >
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                In practice you would choose the nearest available pulley size
                (e.g. 5.25 in or 5.5 in) and re-check the resulting RPM with
                this calculator.
              </p>

              <h2>Multi-stage pulley trains</h2>
              <p>
                When you have more than one belt stage (for example, a
                jackshaft), each stage has its own ratio. The
                <strong>overall speed ratio</strong> is the product of the stage
                ratios:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  R<sub>total</sub> = R₁ × R₂ × R₃ × …<br />
                  N<sub>out</sub> = N₁ / R<sub>total</sub>
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The multi-stage tab in this tool lets you enter up to three
                stages and instantly see the final output speed.
              </p>

              <h2>Approximate belt length formula</h2>
              <p>
                For two pulleys with diameters D₁ and D₂ and center distance C,
                an approximate open-belt length is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  L ≈ 2C + (π / 2) · (D₁ + D₂) + (D₂ − D₁)² / (4C)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                This is the formula used in the belt length tab. It is accurate
                when the center distance is reasonably larger than the pulley
                diameters. For very short center distances or idler pulleys,
                consult manufacturer data or CAD.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical tips for pulley speed design</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Check the <strong>maximum safe RPM</strong> for each pulley
                  from the manufacturer.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Keep belt speed within recommended limits for the belt type to
                  avoid excessive wear.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Allow a few percent margin for <strong>belt slip</strong> and
                  motor speed variation.
                </li>
                <li>
                  After installation, verify actual RPM with a tachometer for
                  critical machinery.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>How do I slow down a driven machine?</h3>
              <p>
                To reduce driven RPM, you can either
                <strong>increase the driven pulley diameter</strong> or
                <strong>decrease the driver pulley diameter</strong>. Both
                actions increase the speed ratio N₁ / N₂.
              </p>

              <h3>Does belt thickness affect pulley speed?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes, slightly. The effective pitch diameter is slightly larger
                than the bare pulley diameter because the belt rides on top. For
                most practical calculations, using the pulley outside diameter
                is sufficient, but precision systems may use pitch diameters
                from manufacturer data.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I mix units for pulley diameters?</h3>
              <p>
                No. All diameters in a given calculation must use the same unit
                (all mm or all inches). RPM is independent of length units, so
                you can freely enter RPM in any consistent way.
              </p>
